Corticosterone Data Analysis and Recovery

Raw data

The data were measured on different time period and among different BXD lines

cort<-read.table("Corticosteroiddata.txt",header=T)
cort

The measurement were done between the 14.11.12 & the 23.01.14

  • The first problem we see is that the majority of lines measurement were performed into lines-batch (i.g. All BXD50 were done 10.04.13 and not dispatched among batch)

  • However, some lines were dispatch among 3 batches (displayed as red color in figures bellow), we could use it to correct for time and cort-control level, taking into account genetic diversity of the lines we observe. Other lines are nested into the batches.

We quickly filter old strains and separate Ctl - SD conditions

cort<-cort[-which(cort$BXD.Lines %in% c("BXD063","BXD029","BXD005","BXD029_TLR4","BXD032")),]
cortNSD<-cort[cort$Condition=="nsd",]
cortSD<-cort[cort$Condition=="sd",]

Heritability computation

# Function to compute heritability

h2Compute<-function(x,y){
  anovares<-aov(x ~ y)
  Va<-summary(anovares)[[1]][1,3]  #is the variance between strains (Mean square for lines effect)
  Vw<-summary(anovares)[[1]][2,3] #is the variance within strains. (Mean square for residuals)
  Vt<-Va+Vw # Total mean variance
  
  # Broad-sense heritability
  H2<-Va/Vt
  # Narrow-sense heritability
  h2<-0.5*Va/(0.5*Va+Vw)
  
  return(h2)
}

Heritability (narrow sense) using replicates mean

for Ctl:

h2Compute(cortNSD$pg.ml,cortNSD$BXD.Lines)
## [1] 0.4999169

for SD:

h2Compute(cortSD$pg.ml,cortSD$BXD.Lines)
## [1] 0.6359878

The heritability is high ! Especially for SD condition.

If we take the old measurement of Shanaz (the one that she through away, because of bad quality) the heritability is much lower (see bellow) ! So we keep good quality data.

cort_bad<-read.table("Corticosteroiddata_bis.txt",header=T)
cort_bad<-cort_bad[-which(cort_bad$BXD.Lines %in% c("BXD063","BXD029","BXD005","BXD029_TLR4","BXD032")),]
cort_badNSD<-cort_bad[cort_bad$Condition=="nsd",]
cort_badSD<-cort_bad[cort_bad$Condition=="sd",]
h2Compute(cort_badNSD$pg.ml,cort_badNSD$BXD.Lines)
## [1] 0.3750117
h2Compute(cort_badSD$pg.ml,cort_badSD$BXD.Lines)
## [1] 0.4855017

Batch effect

We saw above that some batch (e.g. red) have a lower cort level than other (e.g. orange, green)

We can more clearly see this using only mean values:

plot(sort(CortlvlNSD),col=rgb(0,0,0,0),ylab="Cort level (Ctl) Franken")
text(seq(1,length(CortlvlNSD)),CortlvlNSD[order(CortlvlNSD)],labels=gsub("BXD","",names(CortlvlNSD))[order(CortlvlNSD)],cex=.7,col=col[order(CortlvlNSD)])

The difference between batches is significant !

But what is lines effect and batch effect ?

Batch effect correction

Let’s try to correct the batch effect using the ‘red’ batch. Within the red batch, the lines were recorded among 3 distinct batch, the data are not nested ! So we take into account the lines effect and cort control effect.

# Read the batcheffectFile.txt, generated by and from the xlsx file
library(xlsx)
## Loading required package: rJava
## Loading required package: xlsxjars
res <- read.xlsx("BatchEffect.xlsx", 1) # read the second sheet
cortF<-read.table("Corticosteroiddata.txt",header=T)

# Attribute line factor column
lines<-as.character(cortF$BXD.Lines)
names(lines)<-paste(gsub("BXD0","",lines),cortF$Mice,sep='')
names(lines)<-gsub("BXD",'',names(lines))

res$lines<-lines[as.character(res$Mice)]

# Attribute Condition
cond<-as.character(cortF$Condition)
names(cond)<-paste(gsub("BXD0","",as.character(cortF$BXD.Lines)),cortF$Mice,sep='')
names(cond)<-gsub("BXD",'',names(cond))
res$Condition<-cond[as.character(res$Mice)]

# Data removed it seems... no info
res<-res[-108,]

Fit model

res2<-res[-which(res$Batch %in% c("Batch1","Batch2")),]
#res2<-res
fit<-lm(log(Cort)~CortCtl+Condition+lines,data=res2)
plot(fit)

sfit<-summary(fit)

slope<-sfit$coefficients["CortCtl","Estimate"]
slope
## [1] 0.009328431

Estimate Cort level

## Add Cort Control to cort dataset
names(CortCtl)<- names(CortlvlSD)
cort$CortCtl<-rep(NA,nrow(cort))
for (i in 1:nrow(cort)){
  if (as.character(cort[i,"BXD.Lines"]) %in% names(CortCtl)){
    cort[i,"CortCtl"]<-CortCtl[as.character(cort[i,"BXD.Lines"])]
  }
}

res2<-res[-which(res$Batch %in% c("Batch1bis","Batch2")),]
res2$MiceID<-sub("([0-9]+)","" ,res2$Mice)

for (i in 1:nrow(res2)){
  cort[as.character(cort$BXD.Lines)==res2[i,"lines"] & as.character(cort$Mice)==res2[i,"MiceID"],"CortCtl"]<-res2[i,"CortCtl"]
}

cort <- cort[! is.na(cort$CortCtl),]

#### for Ctl
CortNSD<-cort[cort$Condition=="nsd",]
fit_fixedslope<-lm(log(CortNSD$pg.ml) - slope*CortNSD$CortCtl ~ 1)
intercept<-fit_fixedslope$coefficients

plot(CortNSD$CortCtl,log(CortNSD$pg.ml))
abline(a=intercept,b=slope)

EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl<-exp(intercept+60*slope+fit_fixedslope$residuals)
EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean<-aggregate(EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl,list(CortNSD$BXD.Lines),mean)

# a<-EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl
# names(a)<-CortNSD$BXD.Lines
# a

n<-as.character(EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean$Group.1)
EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean<-EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean$x
names(EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean)<-n
EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean<-EstimatedCortLevel_Ctl_mean[names(CortlvlSD)]

#### for SD
CortSD<-cort[cort$Condition=="sd",]
fit_fixedslope<-lm(log(CortSD$pg.ml) - slope*CortSD$CortCtl ~ 1)
intercept<-fit_fixedslope$coefficients

plot(CortSD$CortCtl,log(CortSD$pg.ml))
abline(a=intercept,b=slope)

EstimatedCortLevel_SD<-exp(intercept+60*slope+fit_fixedslope$residuals)
EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean<-aggregate(EstimatedCortLevel_SD,list(CortSD$BXD.Lines),mean)
n<-as.character(EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean$Group.1)
EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean<-EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean$x
names(EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean)<-n
EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean<-EstimatedCortLevel_SD_mean[names(CortlvlSD)]
